rd.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 11:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=128.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Slowing the Orion Down</span><hr size=1> I imagine this has probably already been covered at some earlier date, but what are the options for slowing down an Orion that is hauling along at full speed?  Certainly you wouldn't want to launch nuclear pellets from the front of the ship for obvious reasons since the ship would probably just crash into the pellet or the crew would be forced to ride through the radioactive fallout.  And I get a gut feeling that chemical propellants won't really be up to the job unless you carry giant craploads of them considering the great speed and mass of an Orion.      <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A> at: 8/24/02 11:28:32 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 838<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 3:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=128.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Slowing the Orion Down</span><hr size=1> An Orion would flip around 180 degrees, with the pusher plate now facing toward the line of motion.  Fire the pulse engine to slow down.  With speed being relative, no need to worry about running into the pulse unit prior to detonation... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 66<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 5:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=128.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Slowing the Orion Down</span><hr size=1> Or a second orion stage can be used for deceleration.<br>
This is inherently practical in fact. The pusher plate<br>
of the second orion stage can face the space in <br>
front of orions path, and be used as an interstellar or interplanetary erosion shield.This also positions the second orion stage for the deceleration burn as you approach your destination. <br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 842<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 5:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=128.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Slowing the Orion Down</span><hr size=1> The added weight of a second massive pusher/shock absorber system would prove to be a penalty.  I wonder, could the pusher plate be used as an atmospheric deccelerator?  Dipping into the upper fringes of a planet's atmosphere, using the friction to slow it down?  Or would the system become too unstable... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 538<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 7:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=128.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Slowing the Orion Down</span><hr size=1> Normally an Orion should be flown pusher forward, which would provide the anti-erosion and radiation protection.<br>
<br>
Aerobraking is possible, but an ablative coating would likely be oozed over its surface.  The pusherplate itself would not normally be designed to withstand sustained high temperature.<br>
