Actually, that's not as flippant as it sounds. Forward described it well in &quot;Saturn Rukhs&quot;, where his travelers rappel down Saturn's rings, using tethers with anchors to spend velocity onto passing chunks in the rings. Lose a bit more velocity, to fall into an inner ring, and latch onto a chunk there to lose more velocity.<br>
I suspect that, like aerobraking, it's just not enough, quickly enough to do anything useful to an Orion's mass at the Orion's relative speeds. You'd have to eat up cargo mass to design for it, and the gain you'd get from it isn't worth it.<br>
 Fire off a few more kilos of Pu. Orion uses tens of km/sec for a single interplanetary course. Aerobraking only accounts for 1 or 2 at a time.<br>
